content.text: A complex element contains other elements and/or attributes.
content.html: A complex element contains other elements and/or attributes.

content.text: A complex element is an XML element that contains other elements and/or attributes.
content.html: A complex element is an XML element that contains other elements and/or attributes.

content.text: There are four kinds of complex elements:
content.html: There are four kinds of complex elements:

content.text: Note: Each of these elements may contain attributes as well!
content.html: Note: Each of these elements may contain attributes as well!

content.text: A complex XML element, "product", which is empty:
content.html: A complex XML element, "product", which is empty:

content.code_html: <product pid="1345"/>

content.text: A complex XML element, "employee", which contains only other elements:
content.html: A complex XML element, "employee", which contains only other elements:

content.code_html:
<employee>
  <firstname>John</firstname>
  <lastname>Smith</lastname>
</employee>

content.text: A complex XML element, "food", which contains only text:
content.html: A complex XML element, "food", which contains only text:

content.code_html: <food type="dessert">Ice cream</food>

content.text: A complex XML element, "description", which contains both elements and text:
content.html: A complex XML element, "description", which contains both elements and text:

content.code_html:
<description>
It happened on <date lang="norwegian">03.03.99</date> ....
</description>

content.text: How to Define a Complex Element
Look at this complex XML element, "employee", which contains only other elements:
content.html: Look at this complex XML element, "employee", which contains only other elements:

content.code_html:
<employee>
  <firstname>John</firstname>
  <lastname>Smith</lastname>
</employee>

content.text: We can define a complex element in an XML Schema two different ways:
content.html: We can define a complex element in an XML Schema two different ways:

content.text: 1. The "employee" element can be declared directly by naming the element, like this:
content.html: 1. The "employee" element can be declared directly by naming the element, like this:

content.code_html:
<xs:element name="employee">
  <xs:complexType>
    <xs:sequence>
      <xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>
      <xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>
    </xs:sequence>
  </xs:complexType>
</xs:element>

content.text: If you use the method described above, only the "employee" element can use the specified complex type. Note that the child elements, "firstname" and "lastname", are surrounded by the <sequence> indicator. This means that the child elements must appear in the same order as they are declared. You will learn more about indicators in the XSD Indicators chapter.
content.html: If you use the method described above, only the "employee" element can use the specified complex type. Note that the child elements, "firstname" and "lastname", are surrounded by the <sequence> indicator. This means that the child elements must appear in the same order as they are declared. You will learn more about indicators in the XSD Indicators chapter.

content.text: 2. The "employee" element can have a type attribute that refers to the name of the complex type to use:
content.html: 2. The "employee" element can have a type attribute that refers to the name of the complex type to use:

content.code:
<xs:element name="employee" type="personinfo"/>


<xs:complexType name="personinfo">


<xs:sequence>


<xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>


<xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>


</xs:sequence>

</xs:complexType>
content.code_html:
<xs:element name="employee" type="personinfo"/>

<xs:complexType name="personinfo">
  <xs:sequence>
    <xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>
    <xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>
  </xs:sequence>
</xs:complexType>

content.text: If you use the method described above, several elements can refer to the same complex type, like this:
content.html: If you use the method described above, several elements can refer to the same complex type, like this:

content.code:
<xs:element name="employee" type="personinfo"/>

<xs:element name="student" type="personinfo"/>

<xs:element name="member" type="personinfo"/>


<xs:complexType name="personinfo">


<xs:sequence>


<xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>


<xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>


</xs:sequence>

</xs:complexType>
content.code_html:
<xs:element name="employee" type="personinfo"/>
<xs:element name="student" type="personinfo"/>
<xs:element name="member" type="personinfo"/>

<xs:complexType name="personinfo">
  <xs:sequence>
    <xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>
    <xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>
  </xs:sequence>
</xs:complexType>

content.text: You can also base a complex type on an existing complex type and add some elements, like this:
content.html: You can also base a complex type on an existing complex type and add some elements, like this:

content.code:
<xs:element name="employee" type="fullpersoninfo"/>


<xs:complexType name="personinfo">


<xs:sequence>


<xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>


<xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>


</xs:sequence>

</xs:complexType>


<xs:complexType name="fullpersoninfo">


<xs:complexContent>


<xs:extension base="personinfo">


<xs:sequence>


<xs:element name="address" type="xs:string"/>


<xs:element name="city" type="xs:string"/>


<xs:element name="country" type="xs:string"/>


</xs:sequence>


</xs:extension>


</xs:complexContent>

</xs:complexType>
content.code_html:
<xs:element name="employee" type="fullpersoninfo"/>

<xs:complexType name="personinfo">
  <xs:sequence>
    <xs:element name="firstname" type="xs:string"/>
    <xs:element name="lastname" type="xs:string"/>
  </xs:sequence>
</xs:complexType>

<xs:complexType name="fullpersoninfo">
  <xs:complexContent>
    <xs:extension base="personinfo">
      <xs:sequence>
        <xs:element name="address" type="xs:string"/>
        <xs:element name="city" type="xs:string"/>
        <xs:element name="country" type="xs:string"/>
      </xs:sequence>
    </xs:extension>
  </xs:complexContent>
</xs:complexType>
